<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-06-22T15:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-06-22T15:36:00-05:00" n="845" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d845">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">818.00/713: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at San José</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Chase</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">San
                                            José</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-06-22T15:00:00-05:36"><hi rend="italic">June 22,
                                            1919, 3 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received
                                        June 25, 8.32 a.m.</hi>]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>Confirming my June 20, 6 p.m. Consul Lawton arrived here last
                                night.</p>
                            <p>It is reported that Federico Tinoco told the Latin American diplomats
                                last night that he had things well in hand here in [omission?] that
                                he could quickly suppress the invasion and the gunboat was going
                                soon as also Consul Chase and he had no reason for quitting as the
                                greatest part of American interests were supporting him.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Chase</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>